While nearly every cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
This makes it clear that it is better to only buy a phone.
In spite this, there are many reasons to get a separate MP3 player.
The choice is entirely based on the use and needs of the future owner.
It is unlikely you will get a top-of-line expensive record player to listen to the newest album by Maxim Turbulenc.
First of all such music products are not available on LPs, but also, from a quality perspective there is no objective reason for it.
If your shelves are filled with art rock, jazz, or blues vinyl records you are likely to dream of a record player like that.
It is the same with travel music, that is compressed music, simply called MP3 music.
There are price and quality categories also.
However, it can be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on an MP3 player, as a Pink Floyd fan can accept twenty-crown headphones from a market hall.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
selection is broad.
Battery life also decides
Some top-level music players can do much more than play music, but also do things most cell phones cannot do by chance.
No modern machine is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the main functions of calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, and can even navigate in some cases.
If we take smart phones and communication devices, you have a small computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle, as no refrigerator knows how to grill and no television can take pictures.
The universal nature of the cell phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the sooner the charger will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the most important energy sources.
Very few cell phones can play music for longer than ten to 12 hours, most of them much less.
In this way, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more efficient.
The reason for this is that inexpensive cell phones will not play for more than a few hours.
If you occasionally make calls in addition to that, to be safe, get another charger for your office - even for more expensive devices.
You will not have this problem with MP3 players, even worse ones last for at least 9 straight hours on one charge.
Other problem occurs when recording music on the cell phone.
The majority of the devices have a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
The music can be recorded directly onto a memory card, but very few card reader can handle the small memory cards used in the cell phones without an adaptor.
For music players, with some exceptions (iPod), you do not need any special software.
It is enough to fill the device with music from the computer.
Most cell phones and music players have already created a music library by themselves, organized by the artist's name, album title, genre or, e.g. user rating.
