First virtual operator to arrive in Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in Czechia is quite advanced and local operators offer practically the same services as their Western European partners.
In spite of this, there is something missing - a virtual operator that would force the classic operators to reduce their prices.
It may be missing for a long time.
The fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe has been written many times on Mobil.cz about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This has also been confirmed by Czech Telecommunications Bureau, which called attention to the fact that the price of a text message is higher than in the rest of the Union.
Following recent European Commission steps in the field of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation may occur - text messages for some Czech mobile operators will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that Czech prices remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there are no competitors who would really like to enter the battle.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks here and over 100% coverage.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, believe that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often followed by the Chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Bureau (CTB) Pavel Dvořák, who has repeatedly claimed that there is no room for another operator in Czechia.
It is probably true that a classical operator with its own network no longer has much chance (for example, it would be very difficult to find frequencies).
Then there is one more opportunity - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the introduction of virtual operators on the mobile market that caused the significant lowering of prices, to which even the classic operators had to respond.
In addition, even before the entry of aggressive competitors such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, similar voices could be heard.
It has turned out that there is a place for such operators and they can be truly successful.
However, we do not have to go far to find examples.
In February this year, we informed you of the start of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
The operator took only half a year to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator.
The same financial group Penta, which owns, among others, U:fon, stands behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the opportunity to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, they require many fewer customers than a classic operator does.
They do not carry the relatively high costs of building, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
This way, virtual operators around the world usually profile themselves as low-cost - they offer inexpensive calls and text messages, which is often balanced by a more limited offer of services.
The way Tesco Mobile in Great Britain can offer text messaging for at least fifty percent less than its competitors.
The example of Mobilking in Poland shows that it can be a good move and a good bet on a novel target group.
This operator is specifically oriented to men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - the operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which runs this virtual operator.
It is hard to say if a concept similar to the one in Poland could catch on here.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický does not believe this:
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the perspective of the offer of services.
No chance in Czech Republic, say mobile operators
It seems to be almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czechia, it will not be Mobilking.
"We have been discussing the expanding of this successful project, but Czech negotiations look very hopeful.
More likely, Mobilking will be launched in other countries in the region, according to Jana Studničková, speaker for the Penta financial group in a phone interview for Mobil.cz.
The female representative also confirmed that current mobile operators in Czechia are not inclined towards this idea.
However, they are trying to do everything they can to prevent any potential competitor.
The GTS Novera group has been without a secret about its interest in launching a virtual mobile operator, and in this way it would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefonica O2 in the area of corporate clients.
"We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only hardwire telecommunication services, but also mobile ones.
The sooner, the better.
We have held repeated negotiations on this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
They have already made progress in the negotiations with some of them, according to the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe there are better times ahead.
