Prague City Mass Transport to operate on chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be written into the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when first travellers board the metro, trams and buses with an electronic coupon in their pockets.
The roughly one hundred thousand people with their own Opencard at this time can get this coupon.
Travellers can buy a 30-day, 90-day and year-long coupon (which will be valid from January 1, 2009) and added it to their chip card at the info centres and branches of the Transport Company at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
In the morning, coupons are also available over the Internet on the website of the Transport Company, www.dpp.cz.
By afternoon, more than four hundred customers have used the service.
The beginning users of Internet shopping will forget about the vending windows in metro stations, where up to now they have had to often stand in long lines for paper tickets.
The coupon can be purchased over the Internet and it will be added to the Opencard at one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
The counter is available for travellers with trained staff who will help them with Internet purchases and will also add the purchased coupon to their card.
In addition to libraries, it will also be possible to add the electronic coupons to the Opencard at the self-service machines which have been set up in several vestibules of the metro.
What do self-service machines look like?
The red ones are like ticket validation machines, and travellers may have already seen them in metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
Currently there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty of them.
Coupon check by self-service machine instead of driver
The basic steps to use the self-service machines are simple.
All you have to do is insert the Opencard chip card, and the pre-paid card automatically adds to it.
The electronic coupons are now valid not only in the capital city but also in its surroundings.
The trains and buses numbered 300 to 499 are mainly used by inhabitants of Central Bohemian towns to travel to the capital city.
Passengers in trains included in Prague Integrated Transport are equipped with card reader, with the help of which they can check the time and zone validity of the tickets.
The urban buses have card reader built into the cash register next to the driver's seat.
Upon boarding, it is therefore necessary to not only show the chip card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard on the designated spot on the side of the cash register.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the coupons recorded.
When the traveller needs to confirm the validity of the coupons, there is no easy way to request this information from the driver.
Travelers who do not use urban buses, and will not remember when the validity of a coupon ends, can head for the self-service machines where the coupons are added to the card.
Here the information on the validity of their documents will appear on the machine's screen.
Sudetenlands wanted US referendum
Sudeten Germans requested that Šumava region be incorporated into the United States in 1945.
This is implicit in a letter kept in the South Bohemia Research Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we wish to live under the patronage of the United States.
The Sudeten Germans believed to have addressed the USA with a similar wish.
This is arising from a letter which was kept in a private archive and now is kept in the South Bohemia Research Library.
In the letter, Germans from Český Krumlov request that the American president not allow the return of the "Šumava region" - occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
'We have understood the situation correctly and we want to be fully certain of the words that American troops are entering German territory not as occupation and enemies, but as liberators' is what is written in the letter, signed by "People who are not indifferent to the future of Šumava'.
Since the annexation by Czechoslovakia only gives Sudeten Germans hope for - knowing Czech national character - brutality, disregard, lack of understanding and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over Šumava forever.
Without considering the opinion of a quarter of a million people you would award this territory to a state foreign to us, which suppresses and oppresses minorities and which has nothing, absolutely nothing, to the victory of the Allied States.
The reason why the authors cannot sign their names was the fear of revenge by the Czech occupations.
If the USA president believes that the Šumava Germans are being persuaded to be part of the USA, it would be enough to organize a referendum in Šumava region on whether its inhabitants want to be part of the USA or live under the United States supervision.
The letter may sound a bit naive, given the current knowledge of post-war history, but some reports suggest it appropriately sketches the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
The Czech Germans had to at least expect that their displacement from the country would be discussed, but almost no of them believed it.
Some expected that the United States and Great Britain would negotiate some type of autonomy for the Sudetenlands.
