Rats have Feelings, too.
When in danger, rats or rodents will run away. Does it mean they feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals have thoughts.
If they act the same way we do, how can it be determined if they also experience the same feelings?
The Internet magazine Edge has been running pieces by famous scientists for years.
In a series, SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a selection of responses to the question, `What do you consider to be true without being able to prove it?'
Animals have feelings, as well as other modes of awareness, but we have not yet proven that they have awareness.
Then we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
As we turn to other species and ask questions about feelings or awareness in general, we are entering difficult terrain, because the hardware is not compatible.
When a rat is in danger, it plays possum, runs away or attacks.
Humans act similarly, leading some scientists to conclude that the subjective experience is similar.
I do not believe that.
There are two aspects of our brain structure that make it difficult to project our subjective experience on animals.
The most common circuits involved in human awareness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short term memory and executive and control functions).
This broad region is more advanced in humans than it is in other primates, and seems to be entirely missing in other creatures.
The human awareness based on the prefrontal cortex is probably different from other primates.
The second distinction is likely to be in human linguistic nature: Because such a large part of human experience is linked to language, it is often believed that human awareness depends on it.
In such cases, animals can be excluded.
If awareness was not dependent on language, it would likely be very different from most of our states of awareness.
It is why it is so difficult to determine what animal awareness may be.
If you have something that is internal and subjective, cannot be measured nor analyzed according to our own experience, then its study requires significant challenges.
The explanation has mostly been focused on conscious awareness, but aside from that, there is another important aspect of awareness that is more scientifically accessible.
Human awareness processes can be studied regardless of their content, and that is exactly what is happening in the study of short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
This approach, followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, is concerned with the neural correlates of awareness rather than the causal mechanisms, which may or may not be identical.
This approach also highlights the role of the prefrontal cortex for generation of the visualization.
What does this mean for feelings now?
Remember that an emotional system like fear is triggered in a brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call fear, therefore, is the mental state we are in when the activity of the brain defense system (or its effects such as physical reactions) is processed through virtual memory.
The emotional aspect of feelings is closely linked to those regions of the cortex that are unique to primates, and humans in particular.
In combination with the linguistic nature, the result is delicate emotions, because through words and grammar we can differentiate between states and categorize them, in order to project them to others as well.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings are usually generated from more primitive activities in the cortext and brainstem involved with bodily sensations.
Since this network has not changed in human evolution, they say, it may be a cause of cross-species sensations.
In theory, I cannot agree with that, but I consider it improvable.
However, Pankseep argues that what seemed to be fear with rats and humans probably felt like it in both cases.
A roach's response to danger is flight. Does it experience fear?
As far as I am concerned, a mere similarity of actions is not sufficient evidence for an identity of experiences.
The neural comparison is helpful, granted: Rats and humans have similar brainstems, whereas rodents do not even have brains.
What is the brainstem responsible for emotions?
If it can be proven for humans - how would one want to prove it for rats?
I believe rats and other mammals - maybe even rodents (who knows?) - have emotions.
It is not a proof.
Because their emotional sensations are supposedly fundamentally different from ours (since human awareness is based on specific circuits and on language), I prefer to study emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
There is a promise of results on the nerve level here, if measured in rats and humans.
Like I do not study language and awareness in rats, I do not study their emotions, given that I do not even know if they exist.
The latter may be short-sighted, but I prefer to make progress, rather than keep hitting a wall.
I just happen to be a practical emotionalist.
