Speaking while sleeping
Some children speak during the night.
These are not those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but children who talk while sleeping.
The first time it happens, most of the time you get scared but it really does not have that much importance.
This is a mild alteration of sleep, defined as somniloquy.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Most of you have been told to talk in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (just once in life, associated with a high fever episode) or on a more regular basis (e.g. every day, once a week, once a month ...).
There is no single reason to explain the presence of somniloquy.
Occasionally it may be linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, nocturnal enuresis (pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but it is not always the case.
As mentioned above, it may be associated with very high fever, in situations of stress or over excitement.
In any case, this phenomenon is not researched that well.
Even its intensity is extremely variable.
It may happen someone speaking with a very quiet voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper, or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches ...).
In case the event is particularly intense, the child should be observed and possibly a specialist should be consulted to check if the abnormal state of anxiety is caused by any question, thus generated by the child to vent his feelings.
The findings indicate that this is a benign alteration, and there is no specific treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g. insomnia or stress).
What you can do is considering a number of very simple preventive measures, such as:
Please do not over-excite the child before going to sleep.
Suggest calm games and avoid television or series that inspire fear or suggest violence.
Very nervous children who are very difficult to relax need you to use relaxation techniques to help them acquire inner calm.
This will allow child to sleep more peacefully.
Once somniloquy appears, keep calm.
Remember that it is an inoffensive phenomenon for the child and that next day he will not remember anything about it.
Useful Tips
Do not wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is going on, and you just interrupt his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and thus he is resting.
Remember that if he appears very anguished and the episodes have a specific frequency, it is better to consult a doctor or to verify from where such anxiety originates.
If you get what he is saying (which is not the most common situation) do not fall into the trap of making him an interrogation to obtain information.
Do not get anything, because he is sleeping and he is not conscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you only hear what he says but you cannot see what he is thinking about.
Do not ever tell your child you can ask him something during the night to know his secrets.
Not even jokingly.
This can generate huge anxiety.
However, do not worry, it's not serious, just a short episode.
