The psychology of overbidding: what do we spend more money on?
At an auction, they tend to spend more money on a product and overvalue it.
The neurologist and economist researchers of New York University have successfully revealed the neurological-economic basis of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in a competition like eBay, so they usually pay an unrealistic price.
The research aim to map the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
The group of volunteers was playing lottery and another group participated in an auction. In the meantime, the active brain area of the experimenters was examined by functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
The participants had the chance to gain money in both games but during the auction game - in which overbidding the other person plays a major role - the striatum complex, located under the brain cortex, was starting to work upon the person's defeat.
This area of the brain - aside its other functions - plays a role in the self-rewarding mechanism of the nervous system.
The reason for raising the price is based on the avoidance of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In order to justify their theory, the research group conducted financial research as well.
In this research three groups were making bids against someone, under different conditions.
The control group was simply informed about the real value of the certain product and they made their bids.
Other groups received a promise of a further $15 in case of victory.
The third group was provided by 15 dollars before the auction but in case of defeat they would lose this amount.
As a result, the only difference between the two groups was the focus on victory or defeat.
According to the neurologists, the members of the group "playing for not losing money" were ready to make higher bids than the control group or the group "playing for gaining money".
"These results cannot be deducted from any existing economic theory.
The earlier theory explained the phenomenon at auctions by the pleasure of victory and risk avoidance.
The neurological imaging methods helped us to dissolve the contradiction between the two theories in a way that we got to a third explanation at the end.
Hepatitis: when should we turn to a doctor?
Around half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection. In Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned as the main cause of death.
Although the number of Hungarians being infected by hepatitis can reach 100 000, only 7 000 of them are properly treated.
Hepatitis is a collective name of different infectious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
Although there are similar symptoms, such as liver inflammation or jaundice, the nature of the pathogens and the causing diseases is different.
Hepatitis viruses are transmitted in two main forms, depending on the type of the pathogens: hepatitis A and E travel through the food tract (e.g. infected food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses are carried in blood and body fluids (semen, vagina mucus, saliva).
The people who travel often should protect themselves against A and B viruses by vaccination; but there is no vaccination against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear 2–3 weeks after having eaten contaminated food; they are accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal problems, nausea.
The next sign is jaundice appearing on the skin and in the white part of the eye. Additional symptoms include light coloured faeces, dark urine. Recovery can take 2–3 weeks.
Each year and worldwide, 1 million people die of the more serious form of the disease, hepatitis B, causing liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason is that only about one-tenth of the infected receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also lead to serious problems: cirrhosis of theliver or liver cancer if not treated.
Most infected are not even aware of their disease as the pathogens destroy the liver cells over a long period of time, and in many cases the first symptoms emerge 20 or 30 years later.
From this point, early prevention, especially regular screening tests have fundamental significance.
In three groups this illness is highly above average: among people who have received blood transfusion before 1991, drug-addicts and tattoos.
Currently, the number of people infected by chronic hepatitis C is around 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease can be recognised by routine laboratory testing, it is worth seeing a doctor if any symptoms of unknown origin occur.
In case of early recognition, the disease can be cured, the virus can be destroyed, thus the infection stops and cancer can be prevented.
World Hepatitis Day was first organized in 2004 by the organizations representing the infected.
It aims to call attention to chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, the causes of its induction and the significance of early recognition.
