Mp3 players under accusation, they risk hearing.
Listening to high volume music for a prolonged period of time using portable musical devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing loss.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a communication released in Brussels cites the advice given by the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (SCENIHR) of the EU, published today.
According to this scientific advice, 5- 10 % of those who weekly listen to music using portable musical players for more than an hour a day with the device at high volume risk permanent loss of hearing ability.
”I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music players and cellular phones may unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way”, says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings – carries on the EU spokesperson – a clear risk emerges and we have to respond swiftly.
What is most important, we need to sensitize consumers and make this information available to the public.
Additionally, in light of this scientific advice, we need to re-examine existing control systems to ensure they are completely effective and kept up to date with new technology.
Brussels had asked the independent scientific Committee to investigate the problem, seeing the widespread use of portable music players and the increase in young people exposed to the noise they produce.
Scientists confirm that there are reasons for concern and the European Commission will now look at measures to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise from portable music players and related equipment.
Currently, a European security provision already exists which limits the noise level of portable musical players to 100 dB, but concerns about hearing damage caused by excessive exposure to such noise sources are increasing.
It is possible to considerably reduce the damage by resorting to solutions such as reducing the level and duration of the noise exposure.
In the opinion of the EU Scientific Committee, if users of portable musical players listen to high volume (>89 dB) for only 5 hours per week, they are already over the permissible maximum noise limits for workplaces.
People who listen to music under such conditions for longer periods risk permanent loss of hearing ability after a 5 year period.
This is the case for 5-10% of users of such devices and the number can be estimated to be between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
