Elite in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a couple days back with the vote in the House of Representatives against the 700 billion American dollar rescue plan approved by the White House: a large proportion of Americans were more interested in fighting Wall Street than in saving the economy.
The confirmation was given yesterday by the New York Times when it reported that the current crisis is causing a split within the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, in favour of federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, conservative, in favour of Washington and the financial world, particularly strong in the Central and Southern States.
The soul, to be exact, which has become overbearingly alive with the vote mentioned initially.
The latter is but one example of the changes, of the big changes that the current economic earthquake may herald or allow to be seen, not only in the United States but also in all the West and maybe not only here.
Both in USA and Europe the crisis seems to act as a catalyst for a series of phenomenals that have been incubated for some time and which in the new climate have finally emerged.
The first of these phenomena is the massive re-launch of the twin category state-sovereignty in relation to a sort of nationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is a crisis for the financial-banking institutions that have indeed strong links with foreign countries, but which mainly deal with the budgets of individuals or families living in a single nation, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for whoever is in government: and that is how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families that also form the electorate.
In other words the crisis seems to be global but politically it is almost exclusively national problem.
Political internationalism seems to be substantially out of play or to have little to say: the clear evidence of this is the European Union, divided as usual between the different interests and the different state strategies, cannot agree on a common political path.
The government of each State must wait for intervention, bailout and re-launching plans, new rules, and especially financial aid, since that when the worst happens it is the States that have the resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to fix things.
They also have the necessary means and legitimate reasons to use them: two resources of incalculable value, which no market or international organisation could ever dispose of in any way.
This new focus on the state-national element is almost perfectly compatible with the ever increasing importance that recent economic developments give to a coefficient that is closely linked to that element: territoriality.
While we were already convinced that we had entered the reign of the web, of a technologically increasingly sophisticated, immaterial technology, we suddenly realized that our future would be focused on things that are very little material, such as water, harvests, oil.
Accidentally, all are items that can be transported from one place to another but are always tied to a well defined space, to a territory.
The person who becomes the sovereign , probably has more cards in his deck than he who happens to live in a place without crops, oil or water.
The second novelty is a very interesting novelty that however predicts split.
Whoever says Territory, State, Government, always implies Politics, and consequently Leadership.
In this respect the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the other hand the knowledge of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the need for somebody who knows how to handle the situation.
On the other hand a wave of discredit for existing leadership, an economic sort, revealed to be so inadequate and full of grey areas.
And together something ever deeper and in some way disturbing: discredit, intolerance, inadequacy, a sense of remoteness that tends to involve the entire leadership class of an ever-increasing number of Western countries.
The latter seems to spread further into a large section of the population the confidence that their actions are the same ideas as the social elite up to now in favor, their way of feeling and being, their culture in all accepted meanings of the word, to have had their day, and to always be more alien to the majority.
The call for leadership feeds underhandedly a broad but massive movement of delegitimization of the managerial class and of the traditional political structure, manifesting itself in sudden electoral revolts or abrupt twists in the collective moods in recent and recent times, from the rise of the conservative rise in Austria – Bavaria to the collapse of the labor consensus in Great Britain, to the revolt of the American Congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
The traditional elite, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, some would say their formats, are finding it always difficult to comprehend, and thus to represent what is taking place in the deepest layers of western societies and which the economic crisis is strengthening, increasing, potentially agitating.
In face of all this, talking about a "rebellion of the masses" as being the order of the day may be a bit exaggerated.
If one's eyes are wide open, it is not sure.
