Students are being hit by high rents up to 900 Euro for a room.
The rent market for university students is not known for crises.
According to the latest investigation by SUNIA, the tenants' syndicate, renting a single room can cost up to 900 Euro in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
The phenomenon has now become very serious, especially in cities where students are excluded from the right to study due to the high cost of living that their families would have to sustain.
In most cases the rent-offers contain a series of violations: freestyle contracts, unregistered, without rent limits, connected subleases.
According to SUNIA special intervention is needed to cool down the prices.
Looking at the details of the investigation, one can see that in Milan, for a bed-space in the Brianza zone, 450 Euro are required; for a single room, the price ranges from 450 (Black Band zone), to an average price of 800 (Lambiate zone, Udine and Fiera), and up to a maximum of 900 (Victoria zone).
In Florence a bed-space costs on average 350/400 Euro, a room approximately 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate themselves in close proximity to the university, 250/280 Euro are required for a bed-space in a double room, and from 370 to 500 for a single.
In Rome in the central area of the university (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) approximately 600 Euro is the asking price for a single room, 450 Euro for a bed-space in a double room.
Cheaper (550 Euro for a single room) in areas close to the other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
Savings are only possible by moving to the suburbs: 300 Euro for a bed-space and 450 for a single in areas such as Prenestrina, Centocelle and similar places.
In Naples 300/450 Euro are required for a bed-space, for a single room one spends 400 to 600 Euro, with the highest prices found in Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari for a bed-space 250/350 Euro are required, at least 350 for a single.
Smaller cities have lower prices in absolute terms, but they have a higher impact on the local economy.
In cities where renting to non-EU students is more common, such as Perugia, there is a further anomaly: the increase of about 25/30 % of the rent price asked from foreign students compared with that asked from Italian students.
Goodbye old Cinema Paradiso, cities cancel historical theatres
Historical cinematographic theatres close in favor of Multiplex.
"A city without cinema theatres is a blind city, like a face without eyes".
The image offered by Director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in large Italian urban centres but also in provincial towns.
The sidelining process of cinemas, with the birth in the outskirts of large multi-hall theatres and the consequent death by consumption of the single-hall theatres in the central areas of the city, is one of those events that seems unavoidable and incontrovertible and also has all the features of a real cultural crime.
Occasionally, it is historical places full of memories that disappear, a friend who has shared the way and many memories.
The numbers provided by Anec, the main cinema-operators association, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed shop, and the ones to pay the price were above all the main theatres in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna, and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Following Emilia-Romagna, Italy leads with 82 single-hall cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The three Italian regions with the most recent number of new multiplex cinemas registered are the three Italian regions with the most recent number of new multiplex cinemas registered: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
”Italian theatre industry has developed in an irrational way, so new structures are necessary but it is also important that existing ones are kept, because once a theatre closes, not all its patrons may shift to the multiplexes.
Not mention the misuse of funds for operators: the previous debts by the state are about 10 million Euro.
It is disgraceful, from an ethical and moral perspective, that the government does not respect existing laws.
To sustain the sector between 16 and 18 million Euro a year are needed».
The first Italian city to take cover is Bologna, the first Italian city that, being concerned by the closures, has signed a protocol with the municipal administration and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-hall cinemas both in the historic centre and on the outskirts.
The proposed provisions include tax relief for operators and mobility benefits for the public: spectators can enter the traffic-limited zone and have special tariffs for road parking and in some car parks.
It is an initiative I like, says Giuseppe Tornatore.
The fact is that to contrast the excessive power of the multiplex, traditional theatres also need to improve sound and image quality, because the public is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinemas is always important to me, and the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that inspired me to create "New Cinema Paradiso", which I have already thought for for 10 years.
When I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinal in National Street both closed by now, I turn away to not see the posters being blackened by the dust.
