When energy is born from the waves the big plays.
It is an enormous body, that covers 70% of the planet's surface and now the big, international energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources being eyed, and subjected to development by corporates such as Chevron.
The possibility of using water movement energy has been under investigation for hundred years and in the 70s, coinciding with the first oil crisis, research was intensified.
The idea of exploiting marine energy was abandoned around 1980, but now the appeals by the environmentalists and the new increase in oil prices have given a new boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated that in 2007 15 percent of the world's electrical needs could be provided by the use of the seas' uncontrolled motion.
This amount would be double that currently produced by nuclear power stations.
Then there would be the winds and the tides.
Colossi on attack.
The first company to play on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to construct a plant in north Portugal.
The understanding was announced and it looked like a revolutionary step.
Two years on there are more companies betting on marine energy and among these, there are companies that have always been dedicated to traditional energy.
"Chevron is researching oceanic energy technology – a spokesman for a company associated with the US oil giant has declared to the economy daily Wall Street Journal – and is evaluating the possibility of working with us".
The cooperation in question is the obtaining of a permit from the US Energy Commission, necessary to start a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a significant sign, especially if one considers that right in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has set up a new plan for new drilling.
Following Chevron there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to travel the marine energy path and the amounts invested so far, although they are not known in detail, indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to be made ready.
While experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, marine energy does not leave all doubts about its environmental impact.
The plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not appear to have major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, but technologies with higher environmental impact must be implemented.
The choices are diverse: Ocean Power uses a system of buoys connected between themselves.
The thrust of the waves, which makes the buoys move up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floaters.
The pressure turns a turbine into a turbine, which in turn fuels a generator.
The electricity is sent to shore through underwater cables.
The plants are now waiting for federal approval and part of the energy is used by military installations.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, is already producing energy for a commercial centre and parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York's East River.
The water movement when the sea is moving makes the turbines rotate, creating a rotary motion that generates a generator.
Verdant has a long list of clients waiting for the necessary authorisations to benefit from the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Particular interest, declare the people at the Electrical Energy Research Institute, is now being given by the potential of tides.
The tide is more predictable than the wind, the sun, or the waves, and so is more reliable as a source of energy.
The same is the case for tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine, and Alaska, together with others that overlook the coast, have already invested 7.5 million dollars in 2008 and are expected to invest up to 35 million for 2009.
